actuators Wi-Fi or

10
00:00:36,840 --> 00:00:42,480
some other wireless technology is the most
practical means of communication,

11
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:48,040
because of its cost efficiency and easier
integration with other network components.

12
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:54,700
However, it can be the most
vulnerable component of a system,

13
00:00:54,700 --> 00:00:56,940
if it's not securely implemented.

14
00:00:59,120 --> 00:01:04,110
As information is transmitted through
the air, an attacker has potentially

15
00:01:04,110 --> 00:01:08,950
better chances to intercept the
transmission and capture sensitive data.

16
00:01:12,167 --> 00:01:18,878
Wired Equivalence Privacy or
WEP is a cryptographic security protocol,

17
00:01:18,878 --> 00:01:26,360
which was included in the I triple
E 802.11 wireless standard in 1999.

18
00:01:26,360 --> 00:01:32,290
WEP provides wireless security by
simulating physical access controls.

19
00:01:34,040 --> 00:01:38,409
However, WEP is a weak method,
and its password can

20
00:01:38,409 --> 00:01:43,291
be broken in a few minutes
using available hacking tools.

21
00:01:43,291 --> 00:01:46,925
WEP uses Rivest Cipher 4 or

22
00:01:46,925 --> 00:01:51,831
RC4 stream cipher for encryption.

23
00:01:51,831 --> 00:01:57,020
WEP was implemented in three
version with different key sizes.

24
00:01:57,020 --> 00:02:03,110
In each version, a 24 bit random or
pseudorandom initialization vector IV

25
00:02:04,110 --> 00:02:08,820
is contaminated with the key
to generate the RC4 keystream.

26
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:15,200
RC4 is a simple and
fast bit-oriented stream cipher,

27
00:02:15,200 --> 00:02:18,840
which has demonstrated many
significant vulnerabilities.

28
00:02:19,980 --> 00:02:26,361
For this reason, WEP standard is not used
anymore for secure wireless communication.

29
00:02:27,930 --> 00:02:33,650
In order to address the problems
caused by the weaknesses of WEP,

30
00:02:33,650 --> 00:02:37,394
that is to improve the security of Wi-Fi,

31
00:02:37,394 --> 00:02:43,430
an I triple E draft standard was
developed and named 802.11i.

32
00:02:43,430 --> 00:02:49,306
In it's 2003 version,
the Wi-Fi Protected Access protocol or

33
00:02:49,306 --> 00:02:54,180
WPA was introduced as a more
secure replacement for web.

34
00:02:56,060 --> 00:03:01,720
Like WEP, also WPA uses the RC4
stream cipher for encryption.

35
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:08,530
However in WPA
a Temporal Key Integrity Protocol or

36
00:03:08,530 --> 00:03:13,360
TKIP uses the hash function to
mix the initialization vector,

37
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:18,500
IV with a preshared key rather than
simply concatenating them like WEP.

38
00:03:20,020 --> 00:03:24,230
This reduces the effectiveness
of the related key attacks.

39
00:03:25,860 --> 00:03:30,750
For further assurance, the size of
an initialization vector is doubled from

40
00:03:30,750 --> 00:03:34,150
24 bits to 48 bits.

41
00:03:34,150 --> 00:03:39,110
Meaning, in practice, that the reuse time
of an initialization vector increased

42
00:03:39,110 --> 00:03:42,870
from a few hours of WEP
to a few hundred years.

43
00:03:44,310 --> 00:03:48,730
Moreover, by implementing
a packet sequence number,

44
00:03:48,730 --> 00:03:51,839
WPA provides protection
against reply attacks.

45
00:03:53,530 --> 00:03:58,450
It also provides a stronger message
integrity check called Michael compared to

46
00:03:58,450 --> 00:04:03,850
WEP, which uses basic CRC or
cyclic redundancy check.

47
00:04:05,860 --> 00:04:11,569
WPA uses the same hardware as WEP for
encryption in the access points.

48
00:04:13,490 --> 00:04:19,910
Despite its features also WPA suffers
from many security vulnerabilities and

49
00:04:19,910 --> 00:04:24,067
is currently considered
an unsecure protocol for Wi-Fi.

50
