51
00:04:32,610 --> 00:04:38,710
As we discussed earlier, WPA offers
better security compared to WEP,

52
00:04:38,710 --> 00:04:42,950
by using a hash function for
mixing pre-shared keys and

53
00:04:42,950 --> 00:04:48,600
initialization vectors, devising
a sequence counter to avoid reply attacks,

54
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:51,500
and using a better data
integrity check algorithm.

55
00:04:54,450 --> 00:04:59,162
Because of the vulnerabilities
of the WPA protocol,

56
00:04:59,162 --> 00:05:05,132
a new security protocol called
WPA2 was introduced in the 2004

57
00:05:05,132 --> 00:05:10,175
version of the I triple E
draft standard 802.11i.

58
00:05:10,175 --> 00:05:12,669
It provides strong security for Wi-Fi.

59
00:05:14,370 --> 00:05:18,920
WPA2 is based is based on
a new encryption method called

60
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:24,430
Counter Mode Cipher Block Chaining Message
Authentication Code Protocol or CCMP,

61
00:05:25,540 --> 00:05:29,870
which uses
the Advanced Encryption Standard, AES.

62
00:05:31,520 --> 00:05:34,800
AES is a proven strong block cipher,

63
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:40,690
which was published in 2001 by National
Institute of Standards and Technology.

64
00:05:40,690 --> 00:05:42,010
It is still widely used.

65
00:05:44,001 --> 00:05:48,691
Hardware implementation of WPA2 requires

66
00:05:48,691 --> 00:05:53,634
additional components in wireless devices,

67
00:05:53,634 --> 00:05:59,524
because unlike WPA,
it cannot utilize WEP hardware.

68
00:05:59,524 --> 00:06:07,620
Both WPA and WPA2 offer two authentication
modes, personal and enterprise.

69
00:06:07,620 --> 00:06:12,930
In the personal authentication mode,
a pre-shared key is used as a password.

70
00:06:12,930 --> 00:06:16,189
Hence, they are vulnerable
to weak passwords.

71
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:21,880
In the enterprise mode,
a more advanced authentication called

72
00:06:21,880 --> 00:06:26,260
extensible authentication protocol or
EAP is used.

